One of Julius Evola's arguments against paleo-neo-Darwinism was that thoughts of children are never included in the premonitions of sexual intoxication. E.g. one imagines a woman's face contorting in pain or pleasure, but never imagines her with a newborn or at giving birth, etc.

But I recall an old text, where the author bemoaned the late Greek poets for no longer understanding the metaphysical meaning of myths and turning the gods to mere sensual characters. One striking accusation was the poets "wanting to see the goddesses made heavy with pregnancy".

The implication being the goddesses' struggle and form indulging poets' lust. I think unrestrained poetry represents a pseudo-Edenic state in the same way as obscure tribal peoples are not un-evolved, but just the human ruins of civilizations far, far gone and forgotten eons ago.
